english:
  title: Mid-Autumn Reflections in the Year of Jiachen
  author: Jeong Mongju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Last year I watered my horse at the edge of the azure sea,
    Met the autumn festival at the inn in Hamju.
    Distant mountains, falling leaves scatter,
    The moon hangs full and bright across the sky.
    Thousands of army tents lie silent on the sand,
    Border sounds rising from all sides stir the heart to sorrow.
    The general lies high within his felt-lined camp,
    Soldiers in cold iron sing songs of despair.
    The scholar at the tent entrance cannot sleep either—
    In the lonely deep night, we keep vigil with our shadows.
    I rise and gaze toward the southwest,
    Clouds drift across the sky, stretching to Iron Ridge.
    Spring winds promised to bring me home, yet plans go awry;
    Before Mount Fusu, yellow leaves still fly.
    Tonight the autumn moon shines as it did last year,
    Yet last year's wanderer has not returned.
    The courtyard lies desolate with crickets' cries,
    The kitchen grows cold, and servants go hungry.
    This morning brought a letter from my younger brother—
    Our white-haired mother longs to see me.
    'Fortune and fame are not your destiny,
    Year after year you linger on the road—when will you come home?'
    Where will I meet the bright moon next autumn?
    Here I sit alone by the south window, composing verses.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hamju (咸州) was a strategic frontier city in medieval Korea, suggesting the author was on military duty.
  - key: ''
    value: Iron Ridge (鐵嶺) marks the boundary region between Korea and Manchuria, emphasizing the distance from home.
  - key: ''
    value: Mount Fusu (扶蘇山) evokes both literal geography and the classical theme of separation and homesickness.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem uses the recurring autumn moon as a structural and thematic anchor, contrasting the external constancy of nature with the poet's internal displacement and family anxiety.
